<br>
With that said, here's the guide. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
--The Officer Corps<br>
Galadrid, Taansey, Sentry, Aonedil/Meudir, Ilrissa/Elmarra, Teynor, Caedere, Mustela<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><center> * * *</center><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><center> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Sentinent's</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Guide to Living</center><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><center> <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>General Guild Guide</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></center><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Recruiting</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Often times, I hear in guildchat, &quot;Someone's interested in joining the guild. What do I do?&quot; Well, here's the answer. If you feel this person is worthy of being in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Sentinent</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, give their name to one of the Recruiting Officers (RO) for the month, and they will refer the potential recruit to our <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.thesentinent.com">webpage</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. A person is also required to have three recommendations from guild members before they are invited. Also, please put the potential recruit's name on our &quot;Recruiting&quot; board, along with their level, class, and usual hunting area, so our guild members know who to look out for as grouping partners.<br>
<br>
The RO position switches monthly, and it is announced at each guild meeting. If you are unsure of who the present month's RO is, check in the &quot;Guild News&quot; section of the message board. Their names will most likely be listed in the thread detailing the goings-on of the most recent guild meeting.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Officers</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The current officers for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Sentinent</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are Galadrid, Taansey, Aonedil/Meudir, Ilrissa/Elmarra, Teynor, Caedere, Sentry, and Mustela. Contact any of these members if you have a problem with someone in the guild, or a question about the guild in particular.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Twinking</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Twinking is tolerated within the guild, but to a certain extent. We're not about to make a list of all the items in the game, and what level is &quot;too low&quot; for these items. Use your own discretion. However, some things are obvious. A level 1 monk dual-wielding Knuckle Dusters is a little excessive. <br>
<br>
In regards to twinking, please remember that it is not the responsibility of the guild to twink your alternate character(s). It is one thing to ask for help camping an item for your main character, but requesting help to get an item for an alternate is inappropriate. Use your own time to outfit your alternates, not the time of guildmates.  Furthermore, if an item drops on a guild-sponsored raid that your twink could use, please take into consideration the primary guild characters who could also use the item.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> A Note on Main and Alternate Characters</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Personally, I love my alternate characters, and we welcome alts in this guild. However, we distinguish between Mains and Alts in the use of some guild resources for the following reason -- Equality of Access to Resources is Based on Players, not Characters. Imagine that you have one character in the guild and I have six. Since all members have limits on their playing time, there's a limit to the number of all-guild item camps in a month. If all Characters (main and alt) have an equal call on that time, I would have six times the chance you would to benefit. If you figure that item hand-downs are also limited (and items are class-dependent), again, I would get a lot more items if all Characters are treated equally. The solution we chose is to limit some guild resources to Main Characters only. <br>
<br>
A case could be made that the guild gets more benefit from a variety of alts than from a player with only one character, but since the player behind them must then split his or her time among them, the benefit doesn't seem to outweigh the problem. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Teleports et al.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
There are quite a few members of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Sentinent</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> who are capable of teleporting. Please remember, though, that they play the game for the same reason that you do: to have fun and enjoy themselves. If they are reduced to taxi status, this effectively ruins their gaming experience.<br>
<br>
So, how do you go about requesting a teleport? Simply ask in guildchat, &quot;Is anyone available for a teleport?&quot; If you receive no answer, assume that everyone is busy at the moment, and accept that you probably have to walk to your destination. Please, do not single out a member of the guild and ask them personally to teleport you. It may put an unnecessary amount of pressure on their shoulders because they may feel they are obligated to help a guild member. <br>
<br>
The same holds true for any service a guild member may be able to provide, such as resurrections, and other conveniences. Services such as these are not entitlements, and should never be expected as such. Keep in mind, also, that other people's time is not less important than your time, no matter if they are sitting around in East Commons, working on tradeskills, or soloing. It is no-one's place to judge whether another person is at liberty to provide a service to someone. That's their call.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Looting</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
This applies to both guild-only groups and outside of the guild. Pay attention to how loot is divided when you are grouping. If loot is being done in Master Loot fashion (where only one person in the group loots, and then periodically /splits the money), and you are not the Master Looter, do not loot. If loot is being done as FFA-Honor (where each person in the group loots freely, but allowing each group member equal opportunity to loot), do not hog all of the loot, especially if you are a melee character. The casters may be meditating at the time of the kill, and may not have an immediate opportunity to loot. Take only your fair share. If you have looted 10 corpses in a row before the mob's body has a chance to hit the ground, something is wrong. Furthermore, just because you keep /autosplit on and loot every corpse does not mean that every member of the group gets their fair share. Yes, group members will split the money fairly evenly, but items such as Fine Steel and gems will still be monopolized by one person. <br>
<br>
Guild groups usually loot by NBG/FFA-Honor, meaning that everyone loots their fair share, but if a valuable item drops, the class that can make best use of the item automatically gets the item. However, if a class-specific item drops, and no class that can use the item is present in the group, the item is usually /rolled on.<br>
<br>
As an aside, if you arrange a guild group in order to get a certain item for your main, do your best to ensure that the other members of the group get a little something, also. If you are camping a timed spawn with placeholders, perhaps you should allow the other members of the group to loot the placeholders. They're investing their time into helping you out. Try to be considerate of their kindness.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Uses of Guildchat</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Sentinent</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> has always been a friendly, chatty guild, and we will continue to be for as long as the guild is operational. Guildchat is often used as a medium to discuss topics that are entirely unrelated to the game. Much of this is accepted and embraced. However, if you notice that someone is being overly vulgar, obscene, and disrespectful in guildchat, please contact an officer. There is a different between friendly chatter and abuse of the channel.<br>
<br>
On the same topic, usually members of the guild will give a victory &quot;Woot!&quot; whenever they win an item of value. Please, do not ask if you can have the item, even if you intend to buy it. If the guild member wants to offer up the item, they will do so without encouragement. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Guild Treasury</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The guild treasury is available to guild members only, as a means of bettering themselves without breaking the bank.<br>
<br>
The treasury is open to main characters only. If, at any time, you decide to switch the &quot;main&quot; status to another character, you must give any items you had on your other character back to the treasury. Furthermore, please note that continuously switching between your main and an alternate in order to allow other characters access to the treasury will be seen as abuse of the treasury, and all of your characters will be prohibited from using this convenience.<br>
<br>
The complete listing of rules for the treasury is located on the &quot;Treasury&quot; section of the message board. Please contact an officer if you need the password.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Selling of Guild-gotten Items</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
We are not here to police what you can and cannot sell to the general public. If you, personally, kill Pyzjn and get a GBS, it is your right to sell the item. You got the item yourself, therefore it is your choice what you do with it. However, if you decide to sell an item that several guild members helped you obtain, you may want to confer with these members before you sell the item. Remember, they invested their time in helping you get the item, and they may put you on their &quot;Never Again&quot; list when their past kindness has been sold for a profit.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Kill-stealing, Ninja-looting, etc.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
This one should be obvious, but just in case some may not be aware, we are not a guild who advocates the breaking of the Play Nice Policy (PnP).  (The PnP guildlines are located <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.everquest.com/support/conduct.jsp">here</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.)  If any person is found to be breaking the rules of the PnP, be forewarned that it may mean your permanent expulsion from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Sentinent</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
That is to say, if we receive word from a stranger that Joebob, a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Sentinent</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> member, is deliberately training and kill-stealing in Lower Guk, and after thorough investigation, these accusations prove to be true, Joebob will most likely removed from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Sentinent</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><center> <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>General EverQuest Guide</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></center><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Guide to Getting Help</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Everquest is a hard game, deliberately so, and so it's not uncommon to want help. To mention just a few kinds: Rescue (saving someone from a train, say), Corpse Recovery (corpse locates, summons, drags, and rezzes), buffs, bind, SOW, teleport, being a 'bagman', information, food/drink, plat, items, and help hunting or camping. Getting help is something of an art, and this guide is intended to help you master it.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> First, Understand the Transaction</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Helping someone is basically unequal. The helper goes to some effort and inconvenience to spare the asker some amount (usually larger) of effort and inconvenience -- like having to regain the exp from a death, or hunt more carefully unbuffed. It's not an even bargain. The asker gets the benefits, the helper gets the penalties. <br>
<br>
Sometimes people are in a giving mood, and will help just because they want to. More often, they are taking the inconvenience equation into consideration, too. The key to getting help is doing what you can to balance the equation: reduce the inconvenience and/or increase the payoff.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Reduce the Inconvenience</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
One case is something of an exception: you can't reduce the inconvenience to helpers during a rescue, it's an emergency. Still, you can make it easier for people to help you if you use /y (which tells nearby people the direction you're yelling for help from), and do it before you're almost dead, because it will take them some time to locate you (especially if you're running) and to decide how they can help you without ending up dead too. Now, on to reducing inconvenience in more common kinds of help.<br>
<br>
The difficulty is you don't really know how inconvenient a request is-- it depends on what's going on with them. Their character may be standing there doing nothing obvious, but they may be in a serious conversation by /tell, dinner's burning, and their baby's crying at home. You just don't know. <br>
<br>
Here's a thought: Look for someone who's offering what you want. You know they're not busy. <br>
<br>
If no one's offering the help you need, ask, politely, over /ooc. Most people will see that, and it doesn't annoy like /shouting does. Don't repeat more than once every 5-10 minutes. Be patient, one part of inconvenience is the timing. By being patient, you leave the timing to them. If you decide to ask someone, don't make that your first communication, say hello first in some way. Their response will give you some idea of whether they're busy.<br>
<br>
Make the location convenient. Don't ask someone to travel across a zone to help you, if it can be avoided. Offer to go to them. Put some effort in yourself; people are more likely to help you if you don't make them do all the work.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Increase the Payoff</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Express your gratitude. Remember, they didn't have to do this. Offer payment, if you can. Frequently, the offer itself is enough. If you don't have plat to spare, offer something in trade -- buffs, foraged food, something baked or brewed. Ask them if there's anything you can do for them; maybe they need batwings or information. If someone goes way beyond the bounds to help you, thank them in public, over /ooc or /shout. <br>
<br>
Be polite, respectful of their time, appreciative if they do it, and understanding if they don't. Do not press people if they refuse. Don't try to bully or guilt-trip people, and don't try to con them by making a situation seem worse than it is. Actions like these get talked about, and soon there will be very few people willing to help you.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Always Have a Plan B</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
There will be times when no one will help. Decide what you will do if you must deal with the situation by yourself (walk where you need to go, pull much more carefully, log off for tonight and try again tomorrow, put off camping that item). If help isn't available, deal with it, don't take it out on others.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Do Special Abilities Obligate Someone to Aid Others Anywhere, Anytime?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
No, they don't. To take a RL example, just because I know something about troubleshooting computers, that doesn't mean that I can't charge for my expert knowledge, and put limits on who can call on me for what, when and how often.. Just because people can teleport, or do a Rez, that does not mean they are obligated to do so for you. They are free to refuse without reason, or set any terms they like for the service. If the terms are unacceptable, ask someone else, or deal with your situation without it.  <p><IMG SRC="http://firebeetle.homeip.net/mustelasig.jpg" BORDER="0" WIDTH="216" HEIGHT="212"><br><b>Gnome Heretic of the 54th Bone Chip</b><br>Lanys T'Vyl<br>Proud Officer of <a href="http://www.thesentinent.com">The Sentinent</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub30.ezboard.com/uhaldorrodlah.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Haldor Rodlah</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 79<br> <font color=#333333>(3/16/01 4:04:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub30.ezboard.com/fthesentinentfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=251.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Guild guide, of sorts</span><hr size=1> Question....<br>
